<p class="">    <h2>Key Challenges in the Automobile Steering Torque Sensor Market</h2>    <ul>        <li><strong>Technological Complexity:</strong> The integration of steering torque sensors into modern vehicles is becoming increasingly complex due to the advance of technologies like electric power steering (EPS) and automated driving systems. Ensuring compatibility with various vehicle architectures presents a significant challenge for manufacturers.</li>        <li><strong>Cost Pressures:</strong> The rising costs associated with high-quality materials and sophisticated sensor technology put pressure on manufacturers to maintain profit margins while ensuring product affordability for consumers.</li>        <li><strong>Regulatory Compliance:</strong> Strict safety regulations and standards related to vehicle systems require continuous updates and certifications for steering torque sensors, which can impose additional costs and lengthen product development cycles.</li>        <li><strong>Market Fragmentation:</strong> The automobile steering sensor market is increasingly fragmented, with numerous players offering different technologies. This can lead to inconsistencies in quality and performance, making it challenging for consumers to choose the right solutions.</li>        <li><strong>Consumer Awareness:</strong> A lack of awareness about the benefits of advanced steering torque sensors among end users can hinder market growth. Educating consumers on the advantages of such technologies is essential for wider adoption.</li>    </ul>    <h2>Potential Growth Opportunities in the Automobile Steering Torque Sensor Market</h2>    <ul>        <li><strong>Electric & Autonomous Vehicles:</strong> The growing trend toward electric and autonomous vehicles presents a lucrative opportunity for steering torque sensors. As these vehicles rely heavily on advanced steering systems, demand for precise torque sensors is expected to increase, creating new market avenues.</li>       